gins by discussing the disaster and tracing the origins of the storm. He then goes back two hundred years to tell how this particular electric grid was built, showing us the sacrifices people made to create the grids that (usually) connect us to one another. Today’s power grid, says Doheny-Farina, has become more vulnerable than we realize, as demand begins to outstrip capacity in urban centers around the nation. His book reminds us what those grids mean-both positively and negatively-to our electronically saturated lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aElectric power distributionzNew York (State)xCold weather conditions. 0aElectric power failuresxSocial aspectszNew York (State)zPotsdam RegionvCase studies. 0aElectric power failuresxSocial aspectszNew York (State)zPottsdam RegionvCase studies. 0aIce stormszNew York (State)zSaint Lawrence CountyxHistory. 0aPotsdam Region (N.Y.)xSocial life and customsy20th century. 7aNATURE / Essays.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030008977640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030013382040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133820423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300133820/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY